---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'
import Disclaimer from '../../components/Disclaimer.astro'
import VerifyBadge from '../../components/VerifyBadge.astro'
---

<Base
  title="Schools in Bermuda — A Parent's Guide"
  description="A guide to schools in Bermuda for expat parents: private school options, fees, curricula, the public system, application timing, and early years."
>
  <section class="hero" style="padding-block: var(--space-16);">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/move" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Moving</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Schools</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Schools in Bermuda</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        A parent's guide to the private school options, what they cost, how competitive they are,
        and what to do about applications before you arrive.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- REQUIRED disclaimer above the fold -->
      <Disclaimer variant="relocation" />

      <!-- Overview -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-8);">Overview</h2>
      <p>
        Bermuda has a public school system and several private schools. Most expat families with
        children use the private schools — partly because of their international curricula (IB,
        A-Levels), partly because they provide a more consistent transition path to university
        admission overseas. The private schools are well-regarded for a small island, and the
        leading option (Saltus Grammar School) has a strong university placement record.
      </p>
      <p>
        The honest framing on cost: private school in Bermuda is expensive. Annual fees at the
        most competitive schools run approximately $24,000 per student. This is not exceptional
        for the international schools market globally, but it is a meaningful number to factor
        into compensation negotiations — particularly if you have multiple children.
      </p>

      <!-- School comparison table -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Schools at a glance</h2>
      <div class="table-wrapper" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>School</th>
              <th>Type</th>
              <th>Curriculum</th>
              <th>Approx. fees/yr</th>
              <th>Parish</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Saltus Grammar School</strong></td>
              <td>Private, co-ed</td>
              <td>IB, A-Levels</td>
              <td>~$24,000</td>
              <td>Pembroke</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Bermuda High School</strong></td>
              <td>Private, girls</td>
              <td>IB</td>
              <td>~$22,000–24,000</td>
              <td>Pembroke</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Warwick Academy</strong></td>
              <td>Private, co-ed</td>
              <td>IB</td>
              <td>~$15,000</td>
              <td>Warwick</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>The Bermuda Institute</strong></td>
              <td>Private, Adventist, co-ed</td>
              <td>US-aligned / faith-based</td>
              <td>Varies</td>
              <td>Smith's</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Bermuda public schools</strong></td>
              <td>Government</td>
              <td>Bermuda national curriculum</td>
              <td>No fees</td>
              <td>Island-wide</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        <span class="unverified">[Fee figures approximate — verify directly with each school. Fees are reviewed annually and vary by year group.]</span>
        <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-10" sourceLabel="verify with individual schools" sourceUrl="https://www.saltus.bm" />
      </p>

      <!-- Saltus -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Saltus Grammar School</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Saltus Grammar School</strong> is Bermuda's most competitive and academically
        demanding private school. Co-educational, it runs from Reception through to the Sixth Form,
        offering the <strong>International Baccalaureate (IB) Diploma</strong> and <strong>A-Levels</strong>
        at the senior level. The school has a strong record of placing students at UK universities
        (including Russell Group) and US liberal arts colleges.
      </p>
      <p>
        Saltus is the first choice for most expat families who prioritise academic outcomes and
        who are planning a university application process that will be judged internationally.
        Places at popular year groups are competitive — particularly the early years and the
        Sixth Form entry point. <strong>Apply early, as early as you know your move date.</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        Annual fees are approximately <strong>$24,000 per student</strong>.
        <span class="unverified">[verify at saltus.bm — fees change annually]</span>
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://www.saltus.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">saltus.bm</a>
      </p>

      <!-- BHS -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Bermuda High School for Girls</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Bermuda High School (BHS)</strong> is a girls' school in Pembroke, running from
        early years through to the Sixth Form. It offers the <strong>IB Diploma Programme</strong>
        and has a reputation for strong pastoral care alongside academic attainment.
      </p>
      <p>
        BHS is the default choice for families with daughters who want the IB pathway and a
        single-sex environment. It is consistently well-regarded and places students at competitive
        universities overseas. Fees are comparable to Saltus.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://www.bhs.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">bhs.bm</a>
      </p>

      <!-- Warwick Academy -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Warwick Academy</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Warwick Academy</strong> is a co-educational private school in Warwick Parish,
        offering the <strong>IB Diploma Programme</strong> at the senior level. It is generally
        regarded as more affordable than Saltus or BHS — annual fees of approximately
        <strong>$15,000</strong> make it the most cost-effective private IB option on the island.
      </p>
      <p>
        Warwick Academy is a solid choice and should not be dismissed as a lower-tier option
        on price alone. The IB programme is taught to the same international standard. Families
        who want to reduce school fees without leaving the private IB system choose Warwick Academy
        specifically.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://www.warwickacademy.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">warwickacademy.bm</a>
      </p>

      <!-- Bermuda Institute -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">The Bermuda Institute</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>The Bermuda Institute</strong> is a Seventh-day Adventist K–12 school in Smith's
        Parish. It offers a faith-integrated curriculum with a broadly US-aligned academic approach.
        It is the right choice for families who want a religious school environment. Fees and
        enrolment policies should be confirmed directly with the school.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://www.tbi.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">tbi.bm</a>
      </p>

      <!-- Public system -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">The public school system</h2>
      <p>
        Bermuda's public schools are free to attend and serve the majority of Bermudian families.
        The honest note: <strong>Bermuda's public school system has faced well-documented
        challenges with academic performance</strong> over the past two decades. Government reports
        and independent assessments have consistently identified gaps in attainment relative to
        comparable school systems internationally.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is not a reason to dismiss the public schools categorically — individual teachers and
        individual schools vary, and some families have positive experiences. However, it is
        the reason most expat families who have options choose the private sector.
        For families where private school fees are not affordable, the public schools are the
        system — engage with them early, ask about the specific school your child would attend,
        and assess it on its own terms.
      </p>

      <!-- Bermuda College -->
      <h3 style="margin-top: var(--space-6);">Bermuda College</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Bermuda College</strong> is Bermuda's only post-secondary institution. It offers
        associate degrees, diplomas, and certificates in a range of vocational and academic subjects,
        and has transfer arrangements with overseas universities. Students who intend to pursue a
        four-year degree programme typically go overseas — the UK, Canada, and the US are the
        most common destinations.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://www.college.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank">college.bm</a>
      </p>

      <!-- Application timing -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Application timing — do this before you arrive</h2>
      <div class="alert alert-warning" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
        <strong>Apply before you have a confirmed move date if possible.</strong>
        Popular year groups at Saltus and BHS fill well in advance of the September start.
        Do not wait until you have landed in Bermuda to begin the application process.
      </div>
      <p>
        The typical application calendar for the leading private schools:
      </p>
      <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <li><strong>Applications open:</strong> September to November for the following September start</li>
        <li><strong>Entrance assessments:</strong> typically November to January</li>
        <li><strong>Offers:</strong> typically February to March</li>
        <li><strong>In-year admissions:</strong> possible if places are available, but not guaranteed</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Contact the admissions office of each school directly to confirm current timelines.
        The schools are accustomed to dealing with families in the process of relocating and
        will be straightforward about availability and next steps.
      </p>

      <!-- Early years / nursery -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Early years and nursery</h2>
      <p>
        Several private nursery and pre-school options exist across Bermuda's parishes, particularly
        in Pembroke and Paget near Hamilton. Most of the main private schools run their own
        Reception or Kindergarten entry points. Independent nurseries for under-fives are available
        and the quality is generally good.
      </p>
      <p>
        Early years places are in high demand. If you are moving with children under five, contact
        nurseries and school Reception programmes at the same time as you begin the main school
        application process — do not treat them as a secondary consideration.
      </p>

      <!-- Directory CTA -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-top: var(--space-10);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-3); font-size: var(--text-2xl);">Contact details and directory</h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          Full contact details, admissions email addresses, and direct links for all Bermuda schools
          are in the Pilot.BM directory.
        </p>
        <a href="/directory?filter=education" class="btn btn-primary">Browse schools in the directory →</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
